ry<br />very hard. And then they all not only share that one root vma, but the<br />mm/rmap.c code ends up having to walk all their VM's because there<br />could be a page in there somewhere.<br /><br />These loads aren't necessarily very realistic and very much not<br />common, but I think AIM7 actually has one of those cases, iirc.<br /><br />Our anon_vma locking really is some of the more complex parts of the<br />kernel. Not because of the lock itself, but because of the subtle<br />rules about the whole anon_vma chain and how we have to lock the root<br />of the chain etc etc. And under all _normal_ behavior it's not a<br />problem at all. But I personally dread looking at some of that code,<br />because if we get anything wrong there (and it's happened), it's too<br />painful for words.<br /><br />                  Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
